tle>   Re: peeves</span><hr size=1> 1.  As many have mentioned already, people who tell me to taunt or ask me if i'm taunting after they get hit.  WTF do you think I do?  About all I can do is hit the mob, hit taunt, and try to stand close to it.  Yeah, there's kick/disarm and i use that too, but come on, this is pretty basic stuff.  I think I can figure out how to use the freaking taunt button after 63 levels and 90 some odd AA.  Suggesting that I don't use it when it's needed is just insulting.<br>
<br>
2.  On the flip side, there's people who can't take advice from anyone about anything and just give the excuse &quot;i know how to play my class, shut up!&quot;  I'm sorry, but some people obviously DON'T know how.  For instance, I've grouped with clerics who dump mana on expensive quick heals for no good reason and then we have to wait on them to med.  It started way back when divine light entered the game.  I knew so many clerics who would dump divine light on me when a quick heal wasn't needed at all.  It's a huge waste of mana.  Only use the Light/Remedy spells when a fast heal is needed!  That's not rocket science.  It's simple arithmetic.  Some spells are more efficient than others, so use them when you can.  There can also be problems when it's a new area for people.  If i know the area, I may give some advice.  Take it as advice given with good intentions.  Don't get all defensive and refuse to listen.  I can see why some people suck at playing their class when they take the attitude that they know it all already.<br>
<br>
3. Charm.  It's ridiculous how overpowered it is and it's ridiculous how long it's been that way.  In places like BoT, it's especially broken.  I'm sick of seeing little groups of charmers getting all the named.  Thankfully it looks like the nerf is coming soon.<br>
<br>
&quot;9) Clerics who Elixer Heal THEN cast CH...&quot;<br>
<br>
umm.... why would this be a problem?  It's far better than the other way around, especially toward the beginning of a fight.  Elixirs generate virtually no aggro, so if you elixir the tank, you can delay how soon you have to hit them with a direct heal (like CH).   They generally won't even get you aggro from adds that come with a mob, while if you direct heal before adds are under control, you WILL get aggro.  Direct heals have far, far more aggro than any elixir.  <br>
<br>
-- 63 warrior / 62 cleric<br>
